>\n<p>The hemp extract used in this product is the same full-spectrum oil that The Brothers Apothecary uses in all their oil products. It is derived from hemp flowers and contains a full spectrum of terpenes, flavonoids, and cannabinoids, including plenty of CBD. It does contain trace amounts of THC, but at just 0.08%, this amount is well below the recommended maximum of 0.3%.</p>\n<p>While CBD is the compound in hemp that has the most well-understood medicinal applications, many of the lesser-known substances in this product are just as important. These minor cannabinoids, flavonoids, and terpenes all contribute to the entourage effect and help CBD work more effectively. Many of them also have their own benefits.</p>\n<p>The carrier oil used in this product is medium-chain triglyceride (MCT) oil. This is an optimal carrier oil because it does a wonderful job of protecting fragile hemp compounds while making them easier for the body to absorb. MCT also has a fairly neutral taste that most dogs enjoy.</p>\n<p>To help make this product even more palatable, natural peanut oil is added. Unlike a lot of flavored CBD oils, the French-style peanut oil is quite potent. This single-ingredient oil is unrefined, expeller-pressed, lightly filtered, and would be a favorite for many dogs.</p>\n<p>You can easily smell the peanut butter when you use this product. In the name of providing a thorough review, I also tasted it, and I can tell you the peanut butter does a pretty good job of covering up the natural taste of hemp oil.</p>\n<h3>High Concentration for Therapeutic Dosing</h3>\n<p>The Brothers Apothecary Calming K-9 CBD Oil is only available in one size and concentration. Each bottle is 30ml and contains 500mg of CBD. This breaks out to about 16.7mg of CBD per dropper.</p>\n<p>The general recommendation for CBD dosing in dogs is 1 to 5mg per 10 lbs of body weight. For pain management in my dogs, I use the higher end of the dosing spectrum, known as a therapeutic dose.</p>\n<p>Many dog CBD oils contain less than 1mg of CBD per ml, which means you have to use quite a bit to reach a therapeutic dose. This is especially true if you have a large dog. The high concentration of this product makes it a great, more cost-effective option for therapeutic dosing and dosing large dogs.</p>\n<h3>How to Use</h3>\n<p>Like most CBD oil tinctures, this one can be given directly to your dog or mixed in with their food.</p>\n<p>The advantage of direct dosing is that the CBD is absorbed into the body much more quickly, which means you&#8217;ll see the effects faster. If you are using the oil to help your dog stay calm before a stressful event, I recommend dosing this way. Luckily, the peanut oil makes it quite a bit more palatable for this type of administration.</p>\n<p>You can also add this oil to your dog&#8217;s meals for easier dosing.</p>\n<p>Depending on your dog’s needs, you may want to dose them once or twice per day. CBD has a cumulative effect, which means you will see more consistent results the more often you use it.</p>\n<p>The calming effects of this product are generally obvious within about 30 to 45 minutes of giving it to your dog. These results will get more pronounced with consistent use, with peak results after about two weeks. This is about the time I noticed the product affecting my dogs’ mobility, as well. You can expect full results after about three to six weeks.</p>\n<p><img decoding="async" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-716648" src="https://www.dogster.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Dogster_Website-dividers_v1_Oct-1-2024-04-scaled.webp" alt="divider dog paws 3 oct 2024" width="2560" height="308" srcset="https://www.dogster.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Dogster_Website-dividers_v1_Oct-1-2024-04-scaled.webp 2560w, https://www.dogster.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Dogster_Website-dividers_v1_Oct-1-2024-04-600x72.webp 600w, https://www.dogster.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Dogster_Website-dividers_v1_Oct-1-2024-04-800x96.w