-inner su-u-clearfix su-u-trim"><div class="su-box su-box-style-default" id="" style="border-color:#006600;border-radius:0px"><div class="su-box-title" style="background-color:#009906;color:#FFFFFF;border-top-left-radius:0px;border-top-right-radius:0px">Pros</div><div class="su-box-content su-u-clearfix su-u-trim" style="border-bottom-left-radius:0px;border-bottom-right-radius:0px"><div class="su-list" style="margin-left:0px">\n<ul>\n<li><i class="sui sui-check" style="color:#00BF08"></i> Helps maintain a natural pH balance in the gut</li>\n<li><i class="sui sui-check" style="color:#00BF08"></i> Designed for dogs with serious digestive problems</li>\n</ul>\n</div></div></div></div></div><div class="su-column su-column-size-1-2"><div class="su-column-inner su-u-clearfix su-u-trim"><div class="su-box su-box-style-default" id="" style="border-color:#8c0000;border-radius:0px"><div class="su-box-title" style="background-color:#BF000A;color:#FFFFFF;border-top-left-radius:0px;border-top-right-radius:0px">Cons</div><div class="su-box-content su-u-clearfix su-u-trim" style="border-bottom-left-radius:0px;border-bottom-right-radius:0px"><div class="su-list" style="margin-left:0px">\n<ul>\n<li><i class="sui sui-ban" style="color:#BF000A"></i> Not much meat included</li>\n<li><i class="sui sui-ban" style="color:#BF000A"></i> Low in protein</li>\n<li><i class="sui sui-ban" style="color:#BF000A"></i> Very hard</li>\n</ul>\n</div></div></div></div></div></div>\n<p><img decoding="async" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-716648" src="https://www.dogster.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Dogster_Website-dividers_v1_Oct-1-2024-04-scaled.webp" alt="divider dog paws 3 oct 2024" width="2560" height="308" srcset="https://www.dogster.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Dogster_Website-dividers_v1_Oct-1-2024-04-scaled.webp 2560w, https://www.dogster.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Dogster_Website-dividers_v1_Oct-1-2024-04-600x72.webp 600w, https://www.dogster.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Dogster_Website-dividers_v1_Oct-1-2024-04-800x96.webp 800w, https://www.dogster.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Dogster_Website-dividers_v1_Oct-1-2024-04-768x92.webp 768w, https://www.dogster.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Dogster_Website-dividers_v1_Oct-1-2024-04-1536x185.webp 1536w, https://www.dogster.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Dogster_Website-dividers_v1_Oct-1-2024-04-2048x246.webp 2048w, https://www.dogster.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Dogster_Website-dividers_v1_Oct-1-2024-04-250x30.webp 250w" sizes="(max-width: 2560px) 100vw, 2560px" /></p>\n<h2>Buyer’s Guide &#8211; Choosing the Best Dog Treats for Dogs with Sensitive Stomachs</h2>\n<div class="su-youtube su-u-responsive-media-yes"><iframe width="600" height="400" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/YOhly-mBgAM?" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen allow="autoplay; encrypted-media; picture-in-picture" title=""></iframe></div>\n<p>Everyone should put in a bit of research when purchasing their dog treats. However, if your dog has a sensitive stomach, you’ll need to be extremely careful about <a href="https://www.dogster.com/lifestyle/farm-hounds-natural-chews-treats-review" target="_blank" rel="noopener" data-wpel-link="internal">the treat you decide to purchase</a> for them. After all, not only do you want something healthy, but you also want something that isn’t going to upset their stomach.</p>\n<p>Honestly, the only way to figure out if a treat is going to upset your dog’s stomach or not is to have them try it. While you may be able to narrow it down to certain key ingredients that your dog’s stomach doesn’t like, there will always be treats that seem to set them off for no apparent reason.</p>\n<p>However, you can still choose treats as carefully as possible to help avoid a reaction—hopefully. When you’re looking for dog treats for sensitive dogs, the first thing you should check is the ingredient list. Here is what you should look for.</p>\n<h2>Single Sourced Animal Proteins</h2>\n<p>Many dogs are allergic to a particular kind of animal protein, while others only have issues when proteins are mixed together. A dog’s stomach may have problems digesting more than one type of protein at a time.</p>\n<p>For this reason, we only recommend choosing foods that have one type of protein if at all possible. It may go a long way toward reducing your dog’s digestion problems.</p>\n<p>You may even want to match this protein with the food that they are eating. For instance, if your dog is currently eating lamb food and doing fine on it, consider looking for lamb treats as well.</p>\n<figure id="attachment_103420" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-103420" style="width: 810px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" class="size-full wp-image-103420" src="https://dogster.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/austraian-shepherd-dog-having-treat_Christian-Mueller-Shutterstock.jpg" alt="austraian shepherd dog having treat" width="810" height="540" /><figcaption id="caption-attachment-103420" class="wp-caption-text">Image By: Christian Mueller, Shutterstock</figcaption></figure>\n<h2>Easily Digestible Carbs (or None at All)</h2>\n<p>Preferably, you should choose treats that don’t have any added carbohydrates. Freeze-dried meat is a good option, for instance. However, many treats need a starch of some sort to help hold everything together.</p>\n<p>Therefore, you should look for a highly digestible carb, like potatoes.</p>\n<p>However, you don’t want <em>too </em>many potatoes, peas, or similar veggies. When fed in high amounts, these foods have been linked with <a href="https://www.fda.gov/animal-veterinary/outbreaks-and-advisories/fda-investigation-potential-link-between-certain-diets-and-canine-dilated-cardiomyopathy" target="_blank" rel="noopener" data-wpel-link="external">heart problems</a>. Therefore, your best bet is to choose an option that is low in these starches, if it includes them at all.</p>\n<h2>Animal-Based Fats</h2>\n<p>When at all possible, we recommend choosing treats that have added <a href="https://www.dogster.com/dog-nutrition/common-fat-sources-in-dog-food/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" data-wpel-link="internal">animal fats</a>. If the treat uses whole meat, they may not necessarily need any animal fat. However, if added fat is included, you should check to ensure that it is from an animal source, such as salmon oil or chicken fat.</p>\n<p>These fats make the food taste good, and they’re easier for your dog to digest than plant-based fats. Plus, they include the omega 3s that your dog needs to remain healthy.</p>\n<h2>Fiber</h2>\n<p>Fiber is a boon to <a href="https://www.dogster.com/dog-nutrition/best-dog-food-for-digestive-problems/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" data-wpel-link="internal">the digestive system</a>. Most dogs with sensitive digestion could do with more fiber in their diet to help calm their stomachs. For this reason, we recommend looking for treats that have extra fiber in them.</p>\n<p>However, don’t choose treats with low-quality ingredients just because they have fiber—you’re looking for treats that are healthy and fiber-rich.</p>\n<figure id="attachment_35142" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-35142" style="width: 810px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" class="size-full wp-image-35142" src="https://dogster.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/person-giving-dog-a-treat-e1621963777919.jpeg" alt="giving dog a treat" width="810" height="540" /><figcaption id="caption-attachment-35142" class="wp-caption-text">Image By: Omerlavon, Pixabay</figcaption></figure>\n<h2>No Artificial Ingredients</h2>\n<p>Preferably, you should avoid artificial ingredients, like colors and flavors. In many cases, these artificial ingredients are not needed in the least. Your dog does not care about what their food looks like. And, if the food needs added flavor, then it isn’t using high-quality ingredients to begin with.</p>\n<p>Plus, many of these ingredients can have a negative impact on our dogs, especially if they are already having a problem with their digestion. Therefore, look for treats that are all-natural and don’t contain any of these ingredients. Otherwise, your pet may have a hard time digesting them.</p>\n<h2>Probiotics</h2>\n<p>Probiotics are a great option for dogs with digestion problems. Often, it is recommended that these dogs take some sort of probiotic supplement, anyway. However, you cannot overdose on probiotics, so adding a probiotic treat likely couldn’t hurt.</p>\n<p>Luckily, it isn’t terribly difficult to find treats with probiotics. In many cases, quality treats designed for digestion will include them.</p>\n<p>If you need veterinary advice over your dog&#8217;s nutrition, we recommend speaking with a vet.</p>\n<p><span data-sheets-root="1"><p><div class="su-box su-box-style-default pangovet-mention-box" id="" style="border-color:#003e92;border-radius:3px"><div class="su-box-title" style="background-color:#0971c5;color:#FFFFFF;border-top-left-radius:1px;border-top-right-radius:1px">💛 🐶 Speak To a Vet Online From the Comfort of Your Couch!</div><div class="su-box-content su-u-clearfix su-u-trim" style="border-bottom-left-radius:1px;border-bottom-right-radius:1px"> <img decoding="async" class="aligncenter wp-image-3542157 chewy-in-content-image" style="margin-bottom: 15px;" src="https://www.dogster.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/PangoVet_Mention-in-Content_v10_Oct-18-2024-copy.png" alt="PangoVet" width="375" /></p>\r\n<p style="font-weight: 500; text-align: center; line-height: 1.5; font-size: medium !important; margin-bottom: 20px;">If you need to speak with a vet but can&#8217;t get to one, head over to <a href="https://pangovet.com?utm_source=dogster&amp;utm_medium=article&amp;utm_campaign=dog-nutrition/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" data-wpel-link="external"><b>PangoVet</b></a>. It&#8217;s an online service where you can <b>talk to a vet online</b> and get the personalized advice you need for your pet — all at an affordable price!</p>\r\n<p><div class="su-button-center"><a href="https://pangovet.com?utm_source=dogster&#038;utm_medium=article&#038;utm_campaign=dog-nutrition/" class="su-button su-button-style-default" style="color:#FFFFFF;background-color:#FF6600;border-color:#cc5200;border-radius:9px" target="_blank" rel="nofollow" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="color:#FFFFFF;padding:0px 24px;font-size:18px;line-height:36px;border-color:#ff944d;border-radius:9px;text-shadow:none"> Click to Speak With a Vet</span></a></div></div></div></p></span></p>\n<h2>Ingredients to Support Digestion</h2>\n<p>Often, when we’re choosing treats for a sensitive dog, we tend to focus on ingredients to avoid. However, there are lots of ingredients you should consider looking for too.</p>\n<p>For instance, <a href="https://www.dogster.com/dog-nutrition/best-canned-pumpkin-for-dogs/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" data-wpel-link="internal">pumpkin</a> has long been said to improve the digestive health of dogs. Therefore, you may want to consider finding a pumpkin treat to feed to your canine. (However, there is no scientific research on the actual efficacy of pumpkin in improving digestive health, so your mileage may vary heavily.)</p>\n<p>There are lots of other ingredients that are said to help digestion too. Usually, you’ll find these added ingredients in foods that are specifically designed for digestion.</p>\n<figure id="attachment_45939" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-45939" style="width: 800px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" class="size-full wp-image-45939" src="https://dogster.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/Sweet-Potato-Dog-Treats-Recipe.jpg" alt="Sweet-Potato-Dog-Treats-Recipe" width="800" height="531" /><figcaption id="caption-attachment-45939" class="wp-caption-text">Image By: pakornkrit, Shutterstock</figcaption></figure>\n<h2>Our Selection Process For Treats for Dogs With Sensitive Stomachs</h2>\n<p>To create this buyer&#8217;s guide, our writing team and editorial staff checked customer reviews, brand reputation, and veterinary approval ratings to present the dog treats we think should be highlighted for our readers. In some cases, we conducted hands-on testing along with seeing how much our dogs liked the dog treats. All these factors were considered when selecting these listed dog treats to help you make the best purchase for your furry friends.</p>\n<h2>Why Trust Dogster?</h2>\n<p>Since 2004, Dogster has been a trusted brand for dog owners online, which means we have a lot of experience with dog treats. We take pride in promoting the well-being of all dogs—from toy breeds to giant canines. Our in-house veterinarians, writers, and editors examine each product on our lists, ensuring its quality and reputation. As pet owners ourselves, we only want the best for our furry companions. At Dogster, we are transparent about the products we promote. The nutritional information, overall brand reputation, and customer reviews are all considered for these lists. We inform you how we want to be informed.</p>\n<p><img decoding="async" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-716648" src="https://www.dogster.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Dogster_Website-dividers_v1_Oct-1-2024-04-scaled.webp" alt="divider dog paws 3 oct 2024" width="2560" height="308" srcset="https://www.dogster.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Dogster_Website-dividers_v1_Oct-1-2024-04-scaled.webp 2560w, https://www.dogster.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Dogster_Website-dividers_v1_Oct-1-2024-04-600x72.webp 600w, https://www.dogster.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Dogster_Website-dividers_v1_Oct-1-2024-04-800x96.webp 800w, https://www.dogster.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Dogster_Website-dividers_v1_Oct-1-2024-04-768x92.webp 768w, https://www.dogster.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Dogster_Website-dividers_v1_Oct-1-2024-04-1536x185.webp 1536w, https://www.dogster.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Dogster_Website-dividers_v1_Oct-1-2024-04-2048x246.webp 2048w, https://www.dogster.com/wp-con