ebp 800w, https://www.dogster.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Dogster_Website-dividers_v1_Oct-1-2024-04-768x92.webp 768w, https://www.dogster.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Dogster_Website-dividers_v1_Oct-1-2024-04-1536x185.webp 1536w, https://www.dogster.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Dogster_Website-dividers_v1_Oct-1-2024-04-2048x246.webp 2048w, https://www.dogster.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Dogster_Website-dividers_v1_Oct-1-2024-04-250x30.webp 250w" sizes="(max-width: 2560px) 100vw, 2560px" /></p>\n<h2>Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ)</h2>\n<h3>How Do I Make Sure My Pet Fits?</h3>\n<p>To make sure your pet is compatible, you’ll need to measure their height, width, and length <em>when they are lying down. </em>Pets at 16” in length when down are the best fit because this bag is sized at 18&#8243; exterior length, exterior width at 10.5”, and exterior height at 11” (and the inside dimensions are slightly smaller). This bag is best for pets who don’t weigh any more than 15 lbs.</p>\n<h3>I Need To Return My Carrier: What Is the Policy?</h3>\n<p>All unused and undamaged products are welcome to be returned at any time (alongside all their accessories). That being said, all return label fees are charged at cost, but Mr. Peanut’s does offer the unique opportunity to do a no-fee re-purchase if size or styling was an issue. With this, the return label cost is waived. Shipping fees are not refundable, however.</p>\n<p>Mr. Peanut’s urges used products to be donated to<a href="https://www.dogster.com/lifestyle/history-of-animal-shelters" target="_blank" rel="noopener" data-wpel-link="internal"> local animal shelters and rescues</a>, as the company cannot accept them.</p>\n<h3>How Do I Train My Dog To Be Comfortable Inside the Carrier?</h3>\n<p>For dogs that don’t fancy carriers as much as mine does, you can certainly train them to be comfortable. The most important thing is to acclimate them to the bag, and show them that this is a safe and positive space:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Introduce the carrier in your pet’s most comfortable place, such as in the living room at home. Place treats or toys inside to encourage them to check the carrier out.</li>\n<li>Offer food near or inside the carrier, building a positive association. Reward every time they go inside of their own free will!</li>\n<li>Start practicing closing the carrier door while still offering treats and positive reinforcement. Gradually increase the time the dog is inside with the door zipped shut.</li>\n<li>Practice short trips so your pup gets used to the motion and travel aspect of the carrier.</li>\n<li>Remember that consistency and patience are the key to success! Continue offering positive reinforcement.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Cats are a bit more fickle, but my experience has shown that they do enjoy carriers as a safe space once they are used to them. For cats…</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Leave the carrier out and open, and let your cat explore it.</li>\n<li>Make the carrier warm and inviting by offering blankets with your scent, toys, and for food-motivated cats, throw treats in there.</li>\n<li>Feed your cat inside the carrier to build a positive association.</li>\n<li>Practice short sessions with the carrier zipped shut and being carried around.</li>\n<li>If your cat still shows signs of discomfort but a trip is rapidly approaching, consider using veterinary-approved calming aids!</li>\n</ol>\n<p><img decoding="async" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-765131" src="https://www.dogster.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/Mr.-Peanuts-Gold-Series-Expandable-Pet-Carrier-Review-dog-lying-in-carrier.jpg" alt="Mr. Peanut's Gold Series Expandable Pet Carrier Review - dog lying in carrier" width="1500" height="1126" srcset="https://www.dogster.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/Mr.-Peanuts-Gold-Series-Expandable-Pet-Carrier-Review-dog-lying-in-carrier.jpg 1500w, https://www.dogster.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/Mr.-Peanuts-Gold-Series-Expandable-Pet-Carrier-Review-dog-lying-in-carrier-600x450.jpg.webp 600w